Dogecoin is a decentralized and permissionless cryptocurrency, originally created as a joke.

I mined #Dogecoin early on simply because I liked the yellow dog and the Comic Sans font and because the community was so friendly. 

And because my late dog and best buddy was sitting next to my feet at the time, and this made me think: “Sure, why should I mine anything else? Dogs are the best.”

There is no centralized or “official” organization behind Doge and its blockchain. There is no centralized group of devs who became wealthy by creating Doge and hoarding its supply. It is being developed by volunteers from all over the world. Many companies, groups, and solo devs are building for it.

It will never not be funny to see Doge shoulder to shoulder with centralized VC horrors or projects created, first of all, to make their original devs wealthy and powerful.

It is still funny but also very weird to see Doge’s name (and the meme) pushed by figures with immense power and wealth. My years on this social network but also frequent talks in dog parks around the world made me realize that Dogecoin is synonymous with crypto for many, right next to Bitcoin, embedded into popular culture.

While this moves the market, because all crypto (including BTC) moves mostly due to collective speculation and hype, remember to be responsible.

Do not put crucial house money or farm money into crypto. Stay away from leverage. Buy stuff in real life with your crypto when you need to.

Have fun, but understand the risks.
